   <title class="- topic/title ">Brokers, Dealers, and Futures Commission Merchants and the Definition
                    of a Public Business Entity</title>
   <body class="- topic/body ">
      <p outputclass="ps_para_number" id="UUID-7fd03ea1-9f8d-9559-2b2e-9d777be1f8cd_aag-brd5.135" class="- topic/p ">
         <b class="+ topic/ph hi-d/b ">5.135</b> As discussed
                    in the <xref format="dita" class="- topic/xref " href="../../../../aag-brd/aag-brd_preface/aag-brd_preface.dita#UUID-3022d2d5-d163-3012-b64d-aafce1684168">preface</xref> of this guide, in 2017, the AICPA issued a Technical
                    Question &amp; Answer (Q&amp;A) to help preparers and practitioners determine if
                    their organization or client is a public business entity (PBE) as defined in the
                    FASB ASC Master Glossary. Q&amp;A section 7100.16 is specific to brokers,
                    dealers, and futures commission merchants and states that both issuer and
                    non-issuer broker-dealers registered with the SEC are considered PBEs.
                    Therefore, both issuer and nonissuer broker-dealers registered with the SEC
                    would follow effective dates for PBEs when implementing new
                    pronouncements.</p>
